First Analysis, What are the top Brands and Price Points?

TLDR; We'll use the measures we defined in the last section to write some basic queries to understand the Vodka market, and answer a few questions: What are the most popular brands? Which is the most expensive? Does a particular county favor expensive or cheap Vodka? We will then learn how to save a named query and use it as a basic Nested Query.

Definitions

The following sections use these definitions, created in the previous section.

source: iowa is table('bigquery-public-data.iowa_liquor_sales.sales'){
  measure:
    total_sale_dollars is sale_dollars.sum()
    total_bottles is sum(bottles_sold)
    price_per_100ml is state_bottle_retail / nullif(bottle_volume_ml, 0) * 100
    avg_price_per_100ml is price_per_100ml.avg()
}

Most popular vodka by dollars spent

We start by filtering the data to only purchase records where the category name contains 'VODKA'. We group the data by vendor and description, and calculate the various totals. Note that Malloy automatically orders the results by the first measure descending (in this case).

Notice that the greatest sales by dollar volume is Hawkeye Vodka, closely followed by Absolut. A lot more bottles of Hawkeye were sold, as it is 1/3 the price by volume of Absolut.

query: iowa { where: category_name ~ r'VODKA' } -> {
  top: 5
  group_by: vendor_name, item_description
  aggregate: total_sale_dollars, total_bottles, avg_price_per_100ml
}

SELECT 
   iowa.vendor_name as vendor_name,
   iowa.item_description as item_description,
   COALESCE(SUM(iowa.sale_dollars),0) as total_sale_dollars,
   COALESCE(SUM(iowa.bottles_sold),0) as total_bottles,
   AVG(((iowa.state_bottle_retail/(nullif(iowa.bottle_volume_ml,0)))*100)) as avg_price_per_100ml
FROM `malloy-data.iowa_liquor_sales.sales_deduped` as iowa
WHERE REGEXP_CONTAINS(iowa.category_name, r'VODKA')
GROUP BY 1,2
ORDER BY 3 desc
LIMIT 5

Adding a Query to the model.

This particular view of the data is pretty useful, an something we expect to re-use. We can add this query to the model by incorporating it into the source definition:

source: iowa is table('bigquery-public-data.iowa_liquor_sales.sales'){
  measure:
    total_sale_dollars is sale_dollars.sum()
    total_bottles is sum(bottles_sold)
    price_per_100ml is state_bottle_retail / nullif(bottle_volume_ml, 0) * 100
    avg_price_per_100ml is price_per_100ml.avg()

  query: top_sellers_by_revenue is {
    top: 5
    group_by: vendor_name, item_description
    aggregate: total_sale_dollars, total_bottles, avg_price_per_100ml
  }
}

Examining Tequila

Once the query is in the model we can simply call it by name, adjusting our filtering to ask questions about Tequila instead:

query: iowa { where: category_name ~ r'TEQUILA' } -> top_sellers_by_revenue

WITH __stage0 AS (
  SELECT
    group_set,
    __lateral_join_bag.vendor_name__1,
    __lateral_join_bag.item_description__1,
    CASE WHEN group_set=1 THEN
      COALESCE(SUM(iowa.sale_dollars),0)
      END as total_sale_dollars__1,
    CASE WHEN group_set=1 THEN
      COALESCE(SUM(iowa.bottles_sold),0)
      END as total_bottles__1,
    CASE WHEN group_set=1 THEN
      AVG(((iowa.state_bottle_retail/(nullif(iowa.bottle_volume_ml,0)))*100))
      END as avg_price_per_100ml__1,
    ((CASE WHEN group_set=1 THEN
      COALESCE(SUM(iowa.sale_dollars),0)
      END)/MAX((CASE WHEN group_set=0 THEN
      COALESCE(SUM(iowa.sale_dollars),0)
      END)) OVER ())*100 as percent_of_sales__1
  FROM `malloy-data.iowa_liquor_sales.sales_deduped` as iowa
  CROSS JOIN (SELECT row_number() OVER() -1  group_set FROM UNNEST(GENERATE_ARRAY(0,1,1)))
  LEFT JOIN UNNEST([STRUCT(CASE WHEN group_set=1 THEN
    iowa.vendor_name
    END as vendor_name__1,
  CASE WHEN group_set=1 THEN
    iowa.item_description
    END as item_description__1)]) as __lateral_join_bag
  WHERE (REGEXP_CONTAINS(iowa.category_name, r'TEQUILA'))
  AND (REGEXP_CONTAINS(iowa.category_name, r'TEQUILA'))
  GROUP BY 1,2,3
)
SELECT
  vendor_name__1 as vendor_name,
  item_description__1 as item_description,
  ANY_VALUE(CASE WHEN group_set=1 THEN total_sale_dollars__1 END) as total_sale_dollars,
  ANY_VALUE(CASE WHEN group_set=1 THEN total_bottles__1 END) as total_bottles,
  ANY_VALUE(CASE WHEN group_set=1 THEN avg_price_per_100ml__1 END) as avg_price_per_100ml,
  ANY_VALUE(CASE WHEN group_set=1 THEN percent_of_sales__1 END) as percent_of_sales
FROM __stage0
WHERE group_set NOT IN (0)
GROUP BY 1,2
ORDER BY 3 desc
LIMIT 5

Here we can see that Patron Tequila Silver is the most premium brand, followed by Jose Cuervo as a mid-tier brand, with Juarez Tequila Gold more of an economy brand.

Nested Subtables: A deeper look at a Vendor offerings

The magic happens when we call a named query in the same way we would use any other field nesting. In the below query, we can see our vendors (sorted automatically by amount purchased, as well as the top 5 items for each vendor.

query: iowa { where: category_name ~ r'TEQUILA' } -> {
  group_by: vendor_name
  aggregate: total_sale_dollars, avg_price_per_100ml
  nest: top_sellers_by_revenue // entire query is a field
}

WITH __stage0 AS (
  SELECT
    group_set,
    __lateral_join_bag.vendor_name__0,
    CASE WHEN group_set=0 THEN
      COALESCE(SUM(iowa.sale_dollars),0)
      END as total_sale_dollars__0,
    CASE WHEN group_set=0 THEN
      AVG(((iowa.state_bottle_retail/(nullif(iowa.bottle_volume_ml,0)))*100))
      END as avg_price_per_100ml__0,
    __lateral_join_bag.vendor_name__1,
    __lateral_join_bag.item_description__1,
    CASE WHEN group_set=1 THEN
      COALESCE(SUM(iowa.sale_dollars),0)
      END as total_sale_dollars__1,
    CASE WHEN group_set=1 THEN
      COALESCE(SUM(iowa.bottles_sold),0)
      END as total_bottles__1,
    CASE WHEN group_set=1 THEN
      AVG(((iowa.state_bottle_retail/(nullif(iowa.bottle_volume_ml,0)))*100))
      END as avg_price_per_100ml__1,
    ((CASE WHEN group_set=1 THEN
      COALESCE(SUM(iowa.sale_dollars),0)
      END)/MAX((CASE WHEN group_set=0 THEN
      COALESCE(SUM(iowa.sale_dollars),0)
      END)) OVER ())*100 as percent_of_sales__1
  FROM `malloy-data.iowa_liquor_sales.sales_deduped` as iowa
  CROSS JOIN (SELECT row_number() OVER() -1  group_set FROM UNNEST(GENERATE_ARRAY(0,1,1)))
  LEFT JOIN UNNEST([STRUCT(CASE WHEN group_set IN (0,1) THEN
    iowa.vendor_name
    END as vendor_name__0,
  CASE WHEN group_set=1 THEN
    iowa.vendor_name
    END as vendor_name__1,
  CASE WHEN group_set=1 THEN
    iowa.item_description
    END as item_description__1)]) as __lateral_join_bag
  WHERE (REGEXP_CONTAINS(iowa.category_name, r'TEQUILA'))
  AND ((group_set NOT IN (1) OR (group_set IN (1) AND REGEXP_CONTAINS(iowa.category_name, r'TEQUILA'))))
  GROUP BY 1,2,5,6
)
SELECT
  vendor_name__0 as vendor_name,
  ANY_VALUE(CASE WHEN group_set=0 THEN total_sale_dollars__0 END) as total_sale_dollars,
  ANY_VALUE(CASE WHEN group_set=0 THEN avg_price_per_100ml__0 END) as avg_price_per_100ml,
  ARRAY_AGG(CASE WHEN group_set=1 THEN STRUCT(
    vendor_name__1 as vendor_name, 
    item_description__1 as item_description, 
    total_sale_dollars__1 as total_sale_dollars, 
    total_bottles__1 as total_bottles, 
    avg_price_per_100ml__1 as avg_price_per_100ml, 
    percent_of_sales__1 as percent_of_sales
    ) END IGNORE NULLS  ORDER BY  total_sale_dollars__1 desc  LIMIT 5) as top_sellers_by_revenue
FROM __stage0
GROUP BY 1
ORDER BY 2 desc

These nested subtables allow us to view both the high-level information of "who are our top vendors" as well as the supporting detail in one simple Malloy query.

Bucketing the data

The price_per_100ml calculation, defined in the previous section, combines with our new named query to allow for some interesting analysis. Let's take a look at the entire Tequila category, and see the leaders within each price range. We'll bucket price_per_100ml into even dollar amounts, and nest our top_sellers_by_revenue query to create a subtable for each bucket.

At the top we see our lowest cost options at under $1/mL, with the more pricey beverages appearing as we scroll down.

query: iowa { where: category_name ~ r'TEQUILA' } -> {
  group_by: price_per_100ml_bucket is floor(price_per_100ml)
  nest: top_sellers_by_revenue
}

WITH __stage0 AS (
  SELECT
    group_set,
    CASE WHEN group_set IN (0,1) THEN
      floor(((iowa.state_bottle_retail/(nullif(iowa.bottle_volume_ml,0)))*100))
      END as price_per_100ml_bucket__0,
    __lateral_join_bag.price_per_100ml_bucket__0_string,
    __lateral_join_bag.vendor_name__1,
    __lateral_join_bag.item_description__1,
    CASE WHEN group_set=1 THEN
      COALESCE(SUM(iowa.sale_dollars),0)
      END as total_sale_dollars__1,
    CASE WHEN group_set=1 THEN
      COALESCE(SUM(iowa.bottles_sold),0)
      END as total_bottles__1,
    CASE WHEN group_set=1 THEN
      AVG(((iowa.state_bottle_retail/(nullif(iowa.bottle_volume_ml,0)))*100))
      END as avg_price_per_100ml__1,
    ((CASE WHEN group_set=1 THEN
      COALESCE(SUM(iowa.sale_dollars),0)
      END)/MAX((CASE WHEN group_set=0 THEN
      COALESCE(SUM(iowa.sale_dollars),0)
      END)) OVER (PARTITION BY __lateral_join_bag.price_per_100ml_bucket__0_string))*100 as percent_of_sales__1
  FROM `malloy-data.iowa_liquor_sales.sales_deduped` as iowa
  CROSS JOIN (SELECT row_number() OVER() -1  group_set FROM UNNEST(GENERATE_ARRAY(0,1,1)))
  LEFT JOIN UNNEST([STRUCT(CAST(CASE WHEN group_set IN (0,1) THEN
    floor(((iowa.state_bottle_retail/(nullif(iowa.bottle_volume_ml,0)))*100))
    END as STRING) as price_per_100ml_bucket__0_string,
  CASE WHEN group_set=1 THEN
    iowa.vendor_name
    END as vendor_name__1,
  CASE WHEN group_set=1 THEN
    iowa.item_description
    END as item_description__1)]) as __lateral_join_bag
  WHERE (REGEXP_CONTAINS(iowa.category_name, r'TEQUILA'))
  AND ((group_set NOT IN (1) OR (group_set IN (1) AND REGEXP_CONTAINS(iowa.category_name, r'TEQUILA'))))
  GROUP BY 1,2,3,4,5
)
SELECT
  price_per_100ml_bucket__0 as price_per_100ml_bucket,
  ARRAY_AGG(CASE WHEN group_set=1 THEN STRUCT(
    vendor_name__1 as vendor_name, 
    item_description__1 as item_description, 
    total_sale_dollars__1 as total_sale_dollars, 
    total_bottles__1 as total_bottles, 
    avg_price_per_100ml__1 as avg_price_per_100ml, 
    percent_of_sales__1 as percent_of_sales
    ) END IGNORE NULLS  ORDER BY  total_sale_dollars__1 desc  LIMIT 5) as top_sellers_by_revenue
FROM __stage0
GROUP BY 1
ORDER BY 1 asc
